<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="558" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,642,775]" pageId="7" pageNumber="558">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,273,642,667]" pageId="7" pageNumber="558">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Eyes pubescent, contiguous; antennal flagellum usually with 13 flagellomeres, first flagellomere with sensilla coeloconica. In male flagellomeres 4â€“11 usually fused, distal 3 flagellomeres elongate; katepisternum of thorax with at least one seta; femora unarmed, usually slender (
<bibRefCitation author="Wirth" box="[866,1120,714,739]" pageId="7" pageNumber="558" refString="Wirth, W. W. &amp; Grogan, W. L. (1988) The predaceous midges of the World. (Diptera: Ceratopogonidae; Tribe Ceratopogonini). Flora and Fauna Handbook 4. E. J. Brill. New York, 160 pp." type="book" year="1988">Wirth &amp; Grogan 1988</bibRefCitation>
, de 
<bibRefCitation author="Meillon" box="[1166,1424,714,739]" pageId="7" pageNumber="558" refString="de Meillon, B. &amp; Wirth, W. W. (1991) The genera and subgenera (excluding Culicoides) of the Afrotropical Biting Midges (Diptera: Ceratopogonidae). Annals of the Natal Museum, 32, 27 - 147." type="journal article" year="1991">Meillon &amp; Wirth 1991</bibRefCitation>
). This worldwide- distributed genus includes 200 species (
<bibRefCitation author="Borkent" box="[787,947,750,775]" pageId="7" pageNumber="558" refString="Borkent, A. (2015) World species of biting midges (Diptera: Ceratopogonidae). Available from: http: // www. inhs. illinois. edu / research / FLYTREE / CeratopogonidaeCatalog. pdf (accessed 11 February 2015)" type="journal article" year="2015">Borkent 2015</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
